Conditional columns — when and otherwise.

This is the dataframe version of a sequel case-when. You chain a when, with a condition and a value, for each branch, and you finish with an otherwise, giving the default. And you should always provide that otherwise — because without it, any unmatched rows silently become null.

Now here is the key gotcha, and it surprises people coming from regular programming. Every branch is evaluated, for every row. Unlike Python's if-elif, where evaluation stops at the first true condition, Spark computes every single result expression in the chain, for every row, and only then picks the one whose condition matched.

So consider a guard like — when divisor is not equal to zero, compute value divided by divisor, otherwise zero. That does not save you from divide-by-zero. The division is computed for every row, including the rows where the divisor is zero. So warnings, or nulls, can leak through.

There are two safe fixes. One — coalesce the input, so that null propagates harmlessly. For example, value divided by — when divisor equals zero, null, otherwise divisor. Two — pull the unsafe expression out of the chain entirely, into its own with-column that uses null-safe operators.
